This paper deals with visual knowledge adaptation and proposes a new framework for cross-domain network learning for visual categorization. The paper focuses on computer vision and machine learning techniques, which suggests that it is most likely to belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of extreme learning machines, which are a type of machine learning algorithm, indicating that it could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of fidelity terms and manifold regularization, which are techniques used in artificial intelligence and information retrieval, respectively, suggesting that it could belong to the cs.AI and cs.IR sub-categories. Finally, the paper mentions experiments on benchmark visual datasets for video event recognition and object recognition, indicating that it could also belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category.
